{[%evp 0,21,16,16,16,19,19,20,20,20,31,25,25,16,32,32,43,24,54,60,57,56,55,44]
Welcome to this course! This is the first part of a two-course series, where
we will be covering all of Black's options in the QGD. As usual, my idea is to
provide fresh & challenging variations, where you keep several chances to
catch your opponent off-guard. This course deals with the Queen's Gambit
Declined Variation, The Ragozin Variation, and the QGD 4..a6 variation.} 1. d4
d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 (3... a6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3 {should transpose back to
our course lines.}) 4. Nc3 {The starting point of the QGD system.} Be7 {
Black's most trusted move. This is the starting point of the Queen's Gambit
Declined system.} (4... a6 {This line is considered to be slightly dubious
than its more-known counterparts like Ragozin, Semi-Slav and rightly so.
However, black intends to play in a very solid fashion. Therefore, I recommend
a very fresh way of dealing with these positions with} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Qb3 $5 {
played only in a handful of games. Black's main move is} c6 {but there are
other alternatives too.} (6... h6 $5 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gh6g5] intended to stop
Bg5. This has been played by several strong players. I recommend going for the
positional} 7. e4 $5 {with the idea to meet} Nxe4 {with} 8. Qxd5 Nxc3 9. Qxd8+
Kxd8 10. bxc3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Rd8,Rf7][%cal Gc3c4] where we keep good strategic
chances thanks to the extra space and the fact that black cannot castle
anymore.}) (6... Be7 {is met with the typical 'QGD' plan with} 7. Bf4 O-O 8. e3
c6 9. h3 {[%cal Gf3e5,Yf1e2] where White has the ideal QGD position. You will
get to know more about this structure in the QGD chapters.}) (6... c5 {is met
with} 7. Bg5 c4 8. Qc2 {[%cal Yf3e5,Ge2e4] where we look to gain space with e4,
or centralising the knight with Ne5. White keeps good chances to gain an
advantage.}) (6... b5 $6 {is a very well-known trap arising from a different
variation. I recommend going for the cunning} 7. Bg5 Be6 {and now the forced
tactical sequence with} 8. a4 b4 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Nxd5 Qd8 11. e4 c6 {and now
the stunning} 12. Qe3 $3 {with the point to meet} cxd5 {with} 13. exd5 Qxd5 14.
Rc1 $16 {[%cal Gf1c4,Gd4d5,Yf1d3,Yd3e4] intending Bc4-d5/Bd3-Be4. White keeps
a huge advantage in these positions.}) 7. e4 $5 {the sharpest response.} Nxe4 {
this is the only way for black to maintain equality.} (7... dxe4 $6 8. Ng5 Nd5
9. Bc4 Be7 10. h4 $14) ({the most played move} 7... Be7 {is met with} 8. e5 $16
{[%csl Rb6,Rc5,Gd4,Ge5] where White keeps a huge advantage thanks to the extra
space and Black's weaknesses on the Queenside.}) 8. Nxe4 Qe7 {critical. Black
wants to keep f7-guarded.} (8... dxe4 $4 9. Ng5 $18 {gives white a decisive
advantage.}) {and here I recommend going for the very strong} 9. Bd2 $5 $146 {
which is a novelty, and a dangerous one too. The point of this move is to stop
Qb4, and meet} dxe4 {with} 10. O-O-O exf3 11. Re1 Be6 12. Bc4 $40 {with
tremendous attacking chances.}) (4... Bb4 {The Ragozin variation. Here I
recommend going for} 5. Qa4+ {to provoke Black's knight to an inferior square
with} Nc6 {here we go} 6. e3 O-O 7. Qc2 $5 {where Black has a few choices.} Re8
{the most played move. Black vacates the f8-square for the bishop and intends
to push e6-e5 at the right time.} (7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 Bd6 {is a very thematic
way of playing against 7.Bd2. However, this is less effective against our idea
with 7.Qc2. The most testing response to this is to play} 9. O-O e5 10. h3 $5 {
[%cal Gh3g4] covering the g4-square. These positions are quite easy to play
for white.} a6 {the most flexible response for black.} (10... exd4 11. exd4 $14
{[%csl Gc4,Gd4][%cal Gc1g5] gives us an advantage thanks to the extra space
and the lead in development.}) 11. a3 $5 {[%cal Yc4a2,Gd4e5,Gf3d4,Rf2f4,Re3e4]
we are flexible too. Another idea of this move is to prepare Ba2 so that we
can play dxe5-Nd4 followed by f4-e4. A possible idea for black is to play} h6 {
which we meet with} 12. Bd2 {Black finally develops a piece with} Qe7 {which
we can meet with} 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. f4 $1 Bxc3 16. Bxc3 $14 {
[%csl Gc3,Gc4][%cal Gc3f6,Gc4f7] giving us a typical edge. We are not afraid of
} Qxe3+ 17. Kh2 {[%csl Ra8,Gc3,Gc4,Rc8,Re3,Rf6,Rg7,Rg8][%cal Ga1e1,Gc3f6,Yc2g6]
we have enhanced attacking potential on the Kingside.}) (7... b6 {is met with}
8. Bd2 Ne7 9. a3 $14 {where white keeps a small edge because of the pair of
bishops.}) (7... Ne7 $5 {is a rare way of playing. Black is preparing c5 next.
We meet this with the typical} 8. Bd2 {[%cal Ga2a3] intending a3 Bxc3 Bxc3.
After} c5 9. a3 Bxc3 10. Bxc3 {Black players have tried} cxd4 11. Bxd4 Bd7 $5 {
[%cal Ga8c8] intending Rc8. Here, I recommend going for} 12. cxd5 $5 $146 Nfxd5
13. Bd3 {with great practical chances for an advantage.}) 8. Bd2 Bf8 9. a3 $5 {
a very important waiting move. With a3, we keep control of the b4-square,
while anticipating the e6-e5 break.} ({the natural} 9. O-O-O {runs into} Nb4 $1
$17) 9... e5 {the most played response.} (9... h6 $5 {this is the preference
of the top players. Black is still not committing to a plan. I recommend
meeting this with} 10. cxd5 exd5 {and now the novel} 11. h3 $5 $146 {[%cal
Gh3g4] stopping Bg4. The position is quite complex strategically. Even though
this position has never been played before, I go deep in the most natural
systems.} Ne4 {One of the most natural ways to play the position. Black
prepares Bf5.} (11... a6 12. Bd3 Bd7 {is met with} 13. g4 $5 $146 {where we
keep good attacking chances.}) ({preparing Bf5. We meet this with} 11... Ne7
12. Bd3 g6 {and now} 13. g4 $5 {with the idea to meet} Bd7 {with} 14. Ne5 $5 {
[%csl Gd4,Ge3,Gf4,Gg4][%cal Gf2f4] looking to dominate the board. White keeps
good chances to gain an initiative.}) {here I recommend going for} 12. Bd3 Bf5
13. O-O $5 {[%csl Rb7,Rc6,Rd5] where there are several strategic factors in
play. The knight on c6 is misplaced the pawns on b7 & d5 are targets. This is
a very rich position, and with your opponent out of theory, you keep good
chances to catch them in opening preparation.}) ({for} 9... b6 {I recommend
going for} 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Bd3 {black's best bet here is to play} Ne7 {
which we meet with the typical} ({the natural} 11... Bb7 {is met with the
thematic} 12. O-O Rc8 13. b4 $14 {[%csl Gb4,Rc6,Rc7,Gd4] where white keeps a
thematic edge.}) 12. Ne5 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg2g4] with the idea to gain further
space with f4/g4. White keeps good chances here.}) (9... a6 10. Bd3 $14 {
gives us a better version of the typical Ragozin lines.}) 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11.
cxd5 Nxf3+ {trying to spoil our pawn structure.} ({the natural} 11... Nxd5 {
is met with} 12. Nxe5 Rxe5 13. e4 $14 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ye1c1] where we keep an
advantage thanks to the extra space.}) 12. gxf3 {however, we now have the open
g-file for our rook. After} Nxd5 {I recommend going for the rare} 13. h4 $5 {
[%cal Ge1c1,Gf1d3] stopping Qh4. Our plan is to play 0-0-0, followed by
Bd3-Rg1 next.}) 5. cxd5 $5 {a rare, but ambitious way of playing. We resolve
the tension in the centre so that we can opt for our desired setup.} ({it
makes sense to compare the recommendation with} 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 c5 7. cxd5 {
however, the difference is that in these lines, black has the extra option of}
Nxd5 $1 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gd5f4] attacking our bishop.}) 5... exd5 6. Bf4 $5 {
[%cal Gh2h3,Ye2e3,Yf3e5,Gf1d3] with the following setup in mind :
e3-h3-Bd3-Ne5. This is a trendy and fashionable way of meeting the QGD
nowadays. White keeps the same plans as the 'e3-Bd2 Nimzo', but has a better
version as the 'bad bishop' is out on f4.} c6 {the most common way of playing
these positions.} ({in these structures, we typically want to meet} 6... Bf5 {
with} 7. h3 $5 $146 {[%cal Gg2g4,Yf3e5,Rf5g6] intending g4 Bg6 Ne5.}) 7. h3 $5
{a prophylactic measure. This keeps the h2-square for the bishop. We also keep
an eye out for Bf5, which we want to meet with g4.} O-O 8. e3 Nbd7 {the most
natural plan for black in these positions.} (8... Bf5 9. g4 $5 {[%cal Yg4g5,
Yh3h4,Gf3e5] with g5-h4/Ne5 coming up next.}) {After} 9. Bd3 Re8 10. O-O Nf8
11. Bh2 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gf2f4] we have a much better version of the traditional
QGD's. We want to play Ne5-f4 next.} *


