{[%evp 0,31,16,20,20,12,17,20,20,28,25,25,25,16,24,24,37,30,30,13,60,67,107,52,
71,34,47,56,62,63,63,47,56,41] Welcome to the first chapter. We will begin by
examining one of the critical setups of the QGD.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5
4. Nc3 Be7 5. cxd5 $5 exd5 (5... Nxd5 6. e4 $14 {[%csl Re7] gives us a much
better version of the Semi-Tarrasch. White keeps an advantage thanks to the
extra space in the centre.}) 6. Bf4 {The starting point of our system.
Traditionally, people have preferred Bg5 setups/Bf4 setups without cd/cd ed
Bg5 setups over this system. However modern engines have completely revamped
our understanding of these positions. The point of cxd5 is to eliminate all of
black's Nd5 ideas, with ... dxc4-Nd5 or after cxd5. We aim to play
e3-h3-Bd3-0-0-Ne5, followed by Bh2-f4 and establishing a grip over the
position. Another important plan to know is that for ...Bf5, we usually play
quick h3-g4 to dislodge the bishop from the active diagonal.} c6 {[%csl Gd5]
[%cal Gc6d5] black's most played move. This strengthens the d5-pawn.} 7. h3 $5
{a rarer way of playing these positions. This vacates the h2 square for the
bishop (which is useful against Black's idea of playing ...Nh5). Additionally,
this moves helps in pushing g2-g4, in case Black decides to play ...Bf5.} O-O
8. e3 {[%cal Gf1d3] we are now all set to play Bd3, after which we get our
dream setup.} Bf5 $5 {[%cal Gf5d3] the most challenging move strategically.
Black is happy to trade the light-squared bishops in these positions, as it is
usually Black's 'worst placed piece' in these positions.} 9. g4 $1 {our point.
Black now has three critical moves} Be6 (9... Be4 {[%csl Re4] is met with} 10.
g5 {[%cal Gc3e4] with the intention of capturing on e4 next.} Nh5 {the most
testing move.} (10... Ne8 {runs into} 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Nd2 {[%csl Re4][%cal
Gd2e4]} Bxg5 13. Bxg5 Qxg5 14. Nxe4 Qe7 15. Qc2 Nd7 16. O-O-O $14 {[%csl Gd4,
Rd7,Ge4,Re8,Gf1,Rg7][%cal Gh1g1] where white keeps good attacking prospects.
We also have an active knight, and more space in the centre.}) 11. Bxb8 $1 {
not allowing black to spoil our pawn structure with ...Nxf4.} Rxb8 12. Nxe4
dxe4 13. Nd2 {[%csl Re4,Re7,Gf1,Rh5] Usually, opposite-coloured bishops have a
drawish tendency. However, in positions where a side keeps attacking chances,
it becomes a strength.} g6 14. h4 $1 {[%csl Gg5,Rh5][%cal Yf1e2]} c5 $5 {
[%csl Re1] trying to open the position as our king is in the centre.} (14...
Qd5 {runs into the thematic} 15. Qb3 $1 Rfe8 (15... Qxb3 16. axb3 $14 {[%csl
Ra7,Re4] we will win one of the pawns next, and keep good chances to convert.})
16. O-O-O {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gf1c4] we are all set to play Bc4 next, so black
has nothing better than playing} Qxb3 {where after} 17. Nxb3 $14 {[%csl Rc5,
Re4,Rh5][%cal Gb3c5,Gf1e2] we keep good chances to put pressure in the endgame.
}) 15. dxc5 $1 Bxc5 16. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ge1c1,Gf1e2] If we are able to
castle on the Queenside, we will be able to keep great attacking prospects on
the Kingside.} Qe7 $6 (16... Rc8 {runs into} 17. Bh3 $1 Rc6 18. Nxe4 $14) 17.
O-O-O $16 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf1e2]}) (9... Bg6 {is met with the thematic} 10.
Ne5 {[%cal Gh3h4] looking to win the bishop.} Nbd7 (10... Qb6 $143 11. Nxg6
fxg6 (11... hxg6 12. Qc2 $16 {[%csl Gf1,Gf4,Rg6,Rg7]}) 12. Qc2 $14 {[%csl Gf1,
Gf4][%cal Gf1e2,Gh3h4,Ge1c1]}) 11. Nxg6 hxg6 (11... fxg6 {this seems a bit
unnatural, and after} 12. Qb3 $14 {[%cal Gf1d3,Ra2a4,Ra4a5] white keeps a
healthy edge.}) 12. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] We are trying to start a kingside
attack. Black has two logical responses to counter it.} Ne4 {Natural, but after
} ({the natural} 12... Bb4 {is met with} 13. Rc1 $14 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gh4h5] where
we keep the attacking threats.}) 13. g5 $1 $16 {[%csl Re4,Rg6,Rg8][%cal Gh4h5]
Black is in grave danger. Something like} Bb4 {doesn't help, as after} 14. Rc1
Qa5 $2 15. h5 {we are quicker with the attack. After} Nxc3 16. bxc3 Bxc3+ 17.
Ke2 $18 {[%csl Rc3,Ge2,Rg6][%cal Gd1d3,Gh5g6] we have a decisive attack. Our
king is quite safe on f3.}) 10. Bd3 {[%csl Re6] black now has the thematic
'bad bishop'.} c5 {trying to punish us for pushing g4. However, after} ({
the natural} 10... Nbd7 {is met with} 11. Qc2 $14 {[%cal Gf3g5,Ge1g1] where we
keep a clear advantage.} (11. Ng5 c5 $132)) 11. Rc1 Nc6 12. Bb1 {[%csl Rc5,Rd5]
[%cal Gd4c5] we have the typical edge thanks to the weaknesses in the centre.}
Qb6 $5 (12... cxd4 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Rd5,Re6,Gf4][%cal
Gf4e5]}) 13. O-O $1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Yc3a4]} cxd4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 Qxd4
16. exd4 $14 {[%csl Gb1,Re6,Re7,Gf4][%cal Gf1e1] White keeps a risk-free edge
thanks to the active pieces.} *

