{[%evp 0,33,26,20,20,20,20,20,20,20,25,25,24,16,32,30,37,23,60,55,55,44,45,50,
61,7,9,10,6,-1,-15,-5,-3,-45,-52,-53]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7
5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 c6 7. h3 {the starting point of this chapter. We'll cover
Black's options on this move, along with the alternatives for 8...Bf5 on the
next move.} O-O (7... Qb6 {is another possible option. We meet this with the
natural} 8. Qc2 {defending b2, and stopping Bf5. If we are able to play e3-Bd3
next, we will get our dream setup. Therefore, the critical line here seems to
be} g6 $5 $146 ({note that} 8... O-O {is met with} 9. Rc1 $1 $14 {followed by
e3.} ({Instead,} 9. e3 $6 {runs into} Bf5 $1 $11 10. Qxf5 $2 Qxb2 $1)) 9. e3
Bf5 (9... O-O 10. Bd3 $16 {[%csl Gd3,Gf4,Rg7,Rh6] gives us the dream setup.})
10. Qc1 {[%csl Rg7,Rh6] Usually, this sequence isn't supposed to be good.
However, this particular position is quite fine for us because of Black's
dark-squared weaknesses.} O-O 11. Be2 Nbd7 {natural, but blocks the f5-bishop.}
(11... Ne4 {is met with} 12. Nd2 $1 {with the idea to meet} Nxc3 {with} 13.
bxc3 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge3,Rg7,Rh6][%cal Ga4a5,Ga2a4,Yc3c4] after} c5 14. dxc5
Qxc5 15. Nb3 Qc8 16. Nd4 $14 {[%csl Gc3,Rf5,Rg6][%cal Gc3c4,Ge2f3] we have a
great position due to the inclusion of g6.}) 12. g4 $1 {[%csl Rf5] we try to
exploit the poor positioning of the bishop.} Be4 (12... Be6 13. Ng5 $1 c5 14.
Qd2 cxd4 15. exd4 {gives a typical pleasant position. It's important to note
that we are going to meet} Bd6 {with} 16. Nxe6 fxe6 {and now} 17. Bh6 $1 {
preserving the pair of bishops.} Rf7 18. O-O $14 {[%csl Ge2,Re6,Gh6]}) 13. O-O
{[%cal Yf3e1,Gf2f3] with the simple threat of moving the knight away, and then
pushing f3. Black is forced to play} Bxf3 14. Bxf3 $14 {conceding the
advantage of the bishop pair. White has a pleasant game.} Ne8 (14... Rfe8 $6
15. g5 $16 {[%csl Rf6]}) 15. Re1 {[%cal Ge3e4] preparing e4.} Nd6 (15... Bd6 $6
16. Bh6 Ng7 17. e4 $16) 16. e4 dxe4 17. Nxe4 Nxe4 18. Rxe4 $1 $14 {[%cal Ga2a4,
Ga4a5]}) (7... Bd6 {has been tried by Hikaru. Black looks to swap our bishop.}
8. e3 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ge3f4] inviting Black to take, so that we can
establish a grip over e5.} Bf5 $5 (8... Bxf4 $6 9. exf4 Qe7+ 10. Ne5 $14 {
gives us a very pleasant position.}) (8... O-O 9. Bd3 $14 {is also quite
pleasant for us.}) 9. Be2 {forced, as we don't want to trade the bishops.} O-O
10. O-O Qc7 $5 (10... Ne4 11. Bxd6 Nxd6 12. b4 $14 {[%cal Gb4b5,Gd1b3] with
the idea of playing out the typical plan of a4-b5.}) 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 {[%cal
Yh7h6] Black is fine if he gets h6 in, but we exploit this with} 12. Nh4 $1 {
[%csl Rf5] dislodging the bishop. After} Be6 13. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Re6][%cal
Gf2f4,Yh4f3,Yf3g5,Gf3e5] we have a pleasant position.}) 8. e3 Nbd7 {The most
natural way of playing. Black follows the typical IQP plan. However, since we
haven't played Bg5 he has a better version of the standard lines.} (8... Qb6
$1 {is an interesting, yet unplayed option. The point is to meet 9.Qc2 with ...
Bf5!.} 9. Qb3 $1 (9. Qc2 $6 Bf5 $1 $11) 9... Bf5 $1 (9... Be6 {allows us to
get the dream position with} 10. Bd3 {[%csl Re6] after} Nbd7 {we can safely
plan} 11. Qc2 $1 $14 {[%csl Re6] not fearing} c5 12. O-O c4 13. Be2 $14 {
[%csl Rd5,Re6][%cal Gb2b3,Ga2a4,Ga4a5,Yf3e5,Rf3g5]}) (9... Qxb3 10. axb3 $14 {
[%csl Ga1,Ra7,Gf3,Gf4][%cal Gg2g4,Gf1d3,Gc3a4] gives us a typical QGD position.
White keeps a pleasant position with the natural plans.}) 10. g4 Qxb3 (10...
Bg6 {is met with} 11. Nh4 {forcing black to play} Qxb3 12. axb3 {[%cal Gh4g6]
where black is forced to play} Bc2 {we can meet this with} 13. Nf5 Bxf5 14.
gxf5 Nbd7 15. Bd3 $5 {[%csl Gd3,Gf4][%cal Gh1g1] with a pleasant position for
white.}) 11. axb3 Bg6 $1 (11... Bc2 $6 {is premature, as after} 12. Rc1 Bxb3
13. Nd2 $16 {[%csl Rb3] the bishop is trapped.}) 12. Rc1 Nbd7 13. Nh4 $14 {
[%cal Bh4g6,Bf1e2,Bh3h4,Bf2f3]}) (8... Bd6 9. Bd3 {tr.}) 9. Bd3 $14 Re8 10. O-O
Nf8 11. Bh2 $1 {[%cal Bf3e5,Of8g6] the right time. Bh2 is ideal against
black's idea of ...Nf8.} Ng6 12. Ne5 {centralizing the knight at the right
time.} Nxe5 (12... Bd6 $6 13. f4 $14 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd1f3] gives us great
attacking chances.}) 13. dxe5 Nd7 14. Qc2 $1 {provoking} g6 {so that we can
play} 15. e4 $1 d4 16. Ne2 Nc5 17. f4 $16 {[%cal Bf4f5] with a great attack.} *

