{[%evp 0,23,26,20,20,20,20,20,20,20,17,24,16,16,60,-2,22,15,24,24,24,27,23,17,
19,14]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {This
chapter brings us to black's other options in the QGD on 6th move, namely 6...
Bf5.} Bf5 (6... O-O 7. e3 {and now both} Bf5 {or} (7... c6 8. h3) 8. h3 {
should transpose to lines covered in the previous chapter, or the next one.}) (
{trying to dislodge the bishop with} 6... Nh5 {is met with} 7. Bd2 {[%csl Rh5]
where the knight seems misplaced} O-O (7... Nf6 8. h3 O-O 9. Bf4 {should
transpose back to one of the lines after} Bf5 {or} (9... c6)) 8. e3 {[%csl Rh5]
[%cal Gf1d3,Gf3e5,Yf2f4] we now have a modified version of the e3-Nimzo. Black
has the bishop on the desired square, but the knight on h5 is misplaced.} b6 {
we now have a good version of the e3-Bd2 variation of Nimzo.} (8... c5 {
is not a problem as after} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Bd3 Nc6 11. h3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal
Gc3e2,Gd2c3,Ge1g1] We have a thematic IQP position, which is easier for white
to play. We want to play moves like 0-0-Ne2-Bc3 next.} Nf6 12. O-O Re8 13. Ne2
Ne4 14. Bc3 $14) (8... c6 {is not a problem as after} 9. Bd3 {[%csl Gd3,Rh5]
we have our bishop on the active diagonal.} Nd7 10. O-O Nhf6 {Black has to
bring the knight into the game sooner or later.} 11. Qc2 Bd6 (11... h6 12. Rfe1
{is similar to the text.}) 12. Rfe1 h6 13. Re2 $1 {[%cal Ge3e4,Ga1e1]
preparing e4 with all might. White keeps a pleasant position.}) 9. Ne5 $1 Nf6
10. Bd3 {[%cal Yd1f3,Yf3h3,Gf2f4] We'll follow up with Qf3-h3 or f4.} Bb7 11.
O-O c5 12. Qf3 $1 Nc6 (12... Nbd7 13. Qh3 {[%cal Be5d7,Bd3h7]} Nxe5 14. dxe5
Ne4 15. f4 f5 16. Rad1 $14 {[%csl Rd5,Re5][%cal Gd2e1]}) 13. Qh3 h6 14. Rad1
$14 {[%cal Gc3e2,Gf2f4,Gd2e1,Ge1h4] with great control over the position.}) 7.
h3 {As mentioned in the introduction, we want to typically respond with h3 to
early ...Bf5.} Nbd7 8. g4 {the right move order!} (8. e3 c6 $1 9. g4 Bg6 10.
Nh4 Nf8 {is the key difference.}) 8... Bg6 (8... Be4 {is met with} 9. e3 {
and after both} c6 {and} (9... O-O {we transpose to the next chapter.})) (8...
Be6 {[%csl Re6] Black's bishop is passive here. After} 9. Ng5 $1 (9. e3 h5)
9... Nf8 10. e3 {we keep a safe and solid edge.} h6 (10... c6 {runs into the
thematic} 11. Qb3 $1 Qb6 12. Qc2 $14 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ge1c1,Gc3a4,Gg5e6,Ga4c5]}
) 11. Nxe6 Nxe6 12. Be5 $14) 9. Qb3 $1 {The point behind our move order. We
want to exploit the weaknesses in black's camp.} O-O (9... Nb6 $6 10. Nb5 $16 {
[%csl Rc7]}) 10. Bg2 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb3b7] we are all set to take on b7, so
black is forced to play} Nb6 {[%csl Rb6] which we can meet with} 11. a4 a5 12.
O-O $14 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gf3e5] where we remain better due to the active
positioning of our pieces. The knight on b6 is awkward.} *

