{[%evp 0,29,25,25,25,27,23,31,27,27,27,20,12,17,31,13,35,1,15,15,14,16,21,6,12,
16,22,22,28,29,24,19] In this chapter, we will be covering one of the most
logical possibilities for black in the QGD. We will go through the variation
with 6...Bf5 7.h3 c6!?} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. cxd5 exd5 6.
Bf4 Bf5 7. h3 c6 {the starting point of this chapter.} 8. g4 $5 {[%csl Rf5] as
mentioned several times earlier, ...Bf5 is usually met with early g4.} Be4 $5 (
8... Be6 $6 {as we have seen multiple times, the bishop is poorly placed on e6.
} 9. e3 h5 {the only sensible try. Other moves are weaker.} (9... O-O {
transposes to Chapter 6.}) (9... Nbd7 {allows us to get our dream setup with}
10. Bd3 $1 $14 Nb6 (10... c5 11. O-O $14) 11. Qc2 Bd6 12. Ne5 $14 {[%csl Rb6,
Gd3,Ge5,Re6,Gf4]}) 10. g5 Ne4 11. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Rb7]} Qb6 (11... O-O {is
comfortably met with} 12. Qxb7 Nd7 13. Qc7 $1 {neutralizing the initiative.
After} Qxc7 14. Bxc7 Nxg5 15. Nxg5 Bxg5 16. Bd6 $14 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gf1d3,
Ge1d2,Ga1c1] we keep an edge thanks to the weakness on c6.}) 12. Bd3 Qxb3 {
this isn't threatening, and after} 13. axb3 Bb4 14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. Nd2 $14 {
[%csl Re4] white keeps a comfortable advantage.}) (8... Bg6 {is the subject of
discussion of the next chapter.}) 9. e3 Nbd7 {this transposes to a line where
there are a couple of games played by Magnus (from both colours).} (9... Qb6 $6
10. Nxe4 $1 {winning the bishop at the right time.} Nxe4 (10... dxe4 11. Nd2
Qxb2 12. Rb1 $18 {[%csl Rb7,Re4,Re7][%cal Gb1b7,Gd1c2]}) 11. Bd3 $1 {a very
strong move. We are unbothered by the checks.} Qxb2 (11... Qb4+ 12. Kf1 Qxb2
13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Nd2 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ga1b1,Gf1g2] The king is going to be
quite safe on g2.} Qb5+ 15. Kg2 Qd5 16. Rb1 b6 17. Qc2 $14 {[%csl Rc6,Re4]
[%cal Gh1c1,Gc2e4] We will win the e4 pawn next and follow it up by putting
pressure on c6.}) 12. O-O {[%csl Rb7,Re4][%cal Gd3e4,Gf3d2] our king is quite
safe. We are all set to put pressure on e4/b7. Trying to get the knight way
from e4 with} Nc3 {looks threatening, but after} 13. Qe1 {[%cal Ga1c1] with
the idea of Rc1, we are doing very well.} O-O 14. Rc1 Bb4 15. Rc2 Qa3 16. Qc1
Qxc1 17. Rfxc1 $14 {[%cal Gc1b1]}) (9... Bd6 $6 10. g5 {we are happy to take
back on f4 with the pawn, as it increases our central grip.} Bxf4 (10... Nh5
11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Nd2 $18 {[%csl Re4,Rh5]}) 11. gxf6 $16 {
white won comfortably in: 1-0 (49) Adhiban, B (2610)-Sanjay, S (1944) Pollachi
2023}) (9... O-O 10. g5 {transposes to lines we have already checked.}) 10. Be2
Qb6 $5 {Black tries to put immediate pressure on our position.} (10... O-O 11.
O-O {[%cal Oc3e4,Of3e5]} Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Nb6 13. a4 a5 14. Qb3 {gives us a
pleasant position due to the pair of bishops. We aren't better since the
bishop on f3 is misplaced, but white does keep a very pleasant and easy to
play position.}) 11. Qb3 {As usual, we don't mind the queen trades on b3} Qxb3
12. axb3 Bg6 $5 {tried by Nepo.} ({perhaps more accurate was} 12... Bc2 $1 {
with the intention of provoking Rc1, so that the rook is on an inferior square.
} 13. Rc1 Bg6 $1 (13... Bxb3 $6 14. Nd2 $16) 14. Nh4 {[%csl Rc1] this is too
deep for most players, including Nepo, who wasn't able to play out the
sequence as black in a practical game.}) 13. Nh4 {[%csl Ga1] now white keeps a
comfortable edge.} Bb4 (13... Bc2 14. Nf5 $14 {black is forced to give up the
pair of bishops.}) (13... Ne4 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. Bd3 f5 16. Ke2 $14 {also gives
us typical double-bishop advantage.}) 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. f3 $14 {White went to
convert the game comfortably in 1-0 (43) Carlsen, M (2861)-Nepomniachtchi, I 
(2792) Saint Louis 2022.} *

