{[%evp 0,29,31,22,30,-16,4,9,1,9,15,11,11,14,64,1,33,0,0,-5,37,6,6,6,19,4,21,
-13,-1,-1,-1,-1]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4
Bf5 7. h3 c6 8. g4 $5 Bg6 {the starting point of this chapter. Black retreats
with the bishop to the most logical square.} 9. Ne5 $5 {I recommend going for
the most active response.} ({as discussed in the introduction,} 9. e3 {is met
with} Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7f8,Gf8e6] where black is ready to play Nf8-e6 next.}) 9...
Nbd7 {the most logical response.} (9... Qb6 $146 {is met with a very strong
response.} 10. h4 $1 {we aren't afraid of} Qxb2 {due to the possibility of
playing} 11. Qc1 {[%csl Rg6] black has issues with the bishop on g6.} Ba3 $5 {
the most tempting.} ({another equally tempting option was} 11... Qxc1+ 12. Rxc1
Ba3 (12... h6 {is met with} 13. Nxg6 fxg6 14. e3 {[%csl Rb7,Gf1,Gf4,Rg6][%cal
Gc3a4] where the game is largely strategic, but white keeps a solid edge.} Nbd7
(14... Nxg4 $6 15. Nxd5 $3 cxd5 16. Rc8+ Bd8 17. Ke2 $16 {[%cal Gf1h3,Gh1c1]}
Kd7 18. Bh3 $3 h5 19. Rhc1 $18 {[%csl Ra8,Rb8,Rd8,Rh8][%cal Gf2f3]}) 15. Bd3
Kf7 16. h5 g5 17. Bg6+ Ke6 18. Bf5+ Kf7 19. Be5 $14) {we win material here.
After} 13. h5 Bxc1 14. Bxc1 Bc2 {we have the surprising} 15. Kd2 $18 {[%csl
Rc2] where black is about to lose the bishop.}) 12. Rh3 $1 {[%csl Ra3,Rc3]
[%cal Ge5g6,Gh3a3] the rook defends c3, and keeps an eye over the bishop on a3.
Black still has issues with the bishop on g6.} O-O 13. Nxg6 fxg6 (13... hxg6 $4
14. Qxb2 Bxb2 15. Rb1 Ba3 16. Na4 $18) 14. Qxb2 Bxb2 15. Rb1 Bxc3+ 16. Rxc3 Ne4
$1 17. Rf3 {it looks like black is fine after} b5 {but we keep some pressure
with} 18. g5 a5 19. Bh3 {[%csl Rc6] due to the weakness on c6. Black's only to
remain in the game is} b4 {only move} 20. Be6+ Kh8 21. Rc1 Nc3 $1 {but after}
22. Rfxc3 bxc3 23. e3 Na6 24. Rxc3 $44 {we keep good practical chances.}) (9...
Nfd7 $6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. e3 g5 12. Bg3 {[%cal Gd1b3,Ge1c1,Ge3e4] gives us the
typical advantage thanks to the better pawn structure and the pair of bishops.}
) 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. e3 $146 {we now possess the advantage of a pair of bishops
so all we are aiming for is finishing the development comfortably.} Nf8 {
the most logical response.} (11... Qb6 {is met with} 12. Rb1 {[%cal Gf1d3]
followed by the usual moves.} Nf8 13. Bd3 Ne6 14. Be5 $14) (11... Bb4 {is met
with} 12. Bd3 Ne4 13. Kf1 $1 {followed by Kg2. As seen several times already,
we are not afraid to give up the b2-pawn to open up the queenside/safeguard
our king. Our other strategic advantages compensate for the missing pawn.} Bxc3
(13... Nxc3 14. bxc3 Bxc3 15. Rb1 b5 16. Kg2 $14 {[%csl Rc3,Rc6] black
continues to face issues with the pawn on c6.}) 14. bxc3 g5 $5 (14... Nxc3 15.
Qc2 $14 {[%csl Rc3]}) 15. Bh2 $1 Rxh3 (15... Qf6 16. Bxe4 dxe4 17. Kg2 $14 {
[%csl Rb7,Rh3][%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5,Yh2g3,Gh1h3]}) 16. Kg2 Rh6 17. c4 $16 {[%csl
Rb7,Gd3,Re4,Re8,Gg2,Gh2][%cal Gf2f3] We are not afraid of opening up the
position as our king is quite safe. Along with that, opening up the position
while having the advantage of the bishop is quite principled too.}) 12. Qb3 Qb6
13. f3 {[%csl Re4,Gf3,Rg4][%cal Gf3e4,Gf3g4,Gh3h4] a very thematic plan in
these positions. With f3, we cover the e4/g4 squares and look to gain space
with h4 at the right time.} Qxb3 14. axb3 Ne6 15. Bg3 $5 {this is a good
moment to stop memorization. White keeps some pressure due to the activity of
the pieces, the potential to gain space on the kingside, and the advantage of
the pair of bishops.} *

