{[%evp 0,21,18,20,20,20,20,20,20,20,20,0,6,6,43,12,24,28,28,62,50,46,40,40]
Chapters 7 & 8 cover the 4...a6 variation for black in the QGD. I recommend
going for the very rare 6.Qb3!?, which in my opinion, is a very challenging
try against black's system.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 a6 5. cxd5
exd5 6. Qb3 $5 {[%cal Gc1g5] a very cunning move. We have delayed Bg5 in hopes
of catching in a particular move order trick. Black is unable to get Be6-Ra7
in against our setup of Qb3-Bg5.} ({trying to achieve a similar position with} 
6. Bg5 Be6 7. Qb3 Ra7 $1 {[%csl Rb3,Ge6][%cal Gc7c5,Gb8d7] gives black a
comfortable game.}) 6... Be7 (6... b5 7. Bg5 $14 {runs into a well-known trap
from the 6.Bg5 move order.} Be6 $2 {the most natural move in the position.} (
7... c6 8. Qc2 $14 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Ge2e4,Gf3e5]}) 8. Bxf6 $1 {deflecting the
queen.} Qxf6 (8... gxf6 {[%csl Rd5,Rf6,Rf7,Rh7] spoils black's pawn structure,}
) 9. a4 {[%csl Ra6,Rb5] a very concrete moved aimed to provoke ...b4 so that
black loses the control of the c4-square.} b4 10. Nxd5 {this looks very
dangerous due to} Qd8 11. e4 c6 {but we have the stunning} 12. Qe3 $3 {[%csl
Re8][%cal Ge3e8] with the idea to meet} cxd5 13. exd5 Qxd5 {with} 14. Rc1 $16 {
[%cal Gf1d3,Gd3e4,Yf1c4,Yd4d5] with the idea to play Bc4-d5/Bd3-e4 on the next
move.} Be7 (14... Qd6 {doesn't help, as after} 15. d5 Qxd5 16. Bc4 $18 {
[%csl Re6,Re8][%cal Gf3g5,Ge1g1,Gc4e6,Gc1c8,Yg5e6,Rf7e6] black's king is
busted.}) (14... Kd8 15. Bc4 $18 {[%csl Rd8] is a disaster in making for black.
Black is dead and lost after something like} Qd6 16. Ne5 $18 {[%csl Rc6,Rd8,
Rf7,Rh8][%cal Gc4e6,Yb8d7,Ge5c6,Gc1c6,Ye5f7]}) 15. Bd3 $1 {[%csl Ra8,Rd5][%cal
Gd3e4,Ge4a8] This clever move is easy to miss.} Qb7 ({stepping out of the pin
with} 15... Qd7 {doesn't help as after} 16. Be4 Ra7 17. d5 $18 {[%csl Ra7]
[%cal Gf3e5,Re6g4,Ge3a7] black is still losing material.}) (15... Qb3 16. d5 $1
Qxd5 (16... Bxd5 17. Rc8+ $18) 17. Be4 $18) 16. Be4 Qa7 17. Qf4 $18 {[%csl Ra8,
Re6][%cal Gd4d5,Gc1c7] with moves like Rc7/d5 coming up next, it's very hard
to survive this as black.}) (6... h6 {stopping Bg5, has been played by a lot
of players. Here I recommend going for} 7. e4 $1 {with the idea to deflect the
f6-knight.} Nxe4 (7... dxe4 8. Ne5 Qe7 9. Bc4 $18) 8. Qxd5 {and now black has
two critical deviations.} Nxc3 {the most consistent.} (8... Qxd5 {runs into} 9.
Nxd5 Bd6 10. Bd3 Nf6 11. Nxf6+ {where white keeps a comfortable game after}
gxf6 {[%csl Rf6,Rf7,Rh6] due to the spoiled pawn structure.} 12. O-O $14) 9.
Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. bxc3 {[%csl Rb7,Gc3,Gd4,Rd8][%cal Gc3c4,Ra2a4,Ra4a5,Gc1e3,Yf1d3]
with a strategically easier position for white. Black cannot castle, and white
keeps space in the centre. Our usual setup is going to be Be3-Bd3-c4 in these
positions.} Be6 {preventing Bc4.} (10... Bd6 {was played by Grandelius. Black
is looking to get a quick ...Re8.} 11. Be3 Bg4 {black wants to spoil our
kingside pawn structure.} (11... Re8 12. Bd3 Nc6 13. O-O {[%cal Gf3d2,Gc3c4]
followed by c4 gives us a very pleasant position. Please note that for ...Be6,
we go for 14.Nd2 preparing c4.}) 12. Bd3 {we are not bothered though. After}
Nd7 13. h3 Bxf3 14. gxf3 $14 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5,Gh1g1] we keep a
typical advantage of the pair of bishops.}) 11. c4 $5 $146 {the strongest
practical try in my opinion.} (11. a4 {runs into} a5 $5 {where I feel black is
doing fine.}) (11. Be3 Ba3 $1 $11) 11... Bb4+ 12. Bd2 Bxd2+ 13. Kxd2 $14 {
[%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5,Gf1d3,Gd2c3] We keep good chances to press on the Queenside/
in the centre in these endgames. Remember to avoid exchanging pieces as much
as possible.}) (6... Ra7 $6 {runs into} 7. e4 {where black is struggling.} Nxe4
8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. Ng5 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gf1c4]} Qe7 10. Bc4 f6 11. Nf7 $16) ({
another possible idea is to play} 6... c5 {challenging our center. Here we go
for the natural} 7. Bg5 {[%csl Rd5] intending to put pressure on black's
center.} c4 {this gains space, but fixes the weakness on d5.} (7... Nc6 8. Bxf6
gxf6 9. e3 Be6 10. g3 $14 {[%csl Rd5,Rf6,Rf7][%cal Gf1g2] white is better due
to the much better pawn structure.}) 8. Qc2 Bb4 {the only critical try. Black
tries to stop e4.} (8... Be7 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. e4 $14) (8... Be6 9. e4 $14) 9.
e4 $5 {we still go for the break.} dxe4 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Qxe4+ Qe6 12. Ne5 $1
{our point. We are threatening Bxc4 hence is forced to play} f6 (12... Bxc3+
13. bxc3 f6 {transposes.}) 13. Bxc4 Bxc3+ (13... Qe7 $6 {runs into} 14. O-O {
[%csl Re8][%cal Gc3d5] where the king is in heavy danger.} Bxc3 {runs into} 15.
Bf7+ Kf8 16. bxc3 fxe5 17. Bb3 $14 {[%cal Ga1e1] with great attacking chances.}
) 14. bxc3 Qe7 15. O-O $146 fxe5 16. f4 {it seems that black is about to be
crushed in the center, but black can survive with} ({the natural} 16. Rae1 {
runs into} Rf8 $3 17. Qd5 Nc6 $17) 16... g6 $1 17. fxe5 Bf5 {however after} 18.
Qe3 Nc6 19. d5 Na5 20. Be2 O-O 21. e6 $44 {[%csl Ra5,Gd5,Ge6,Rf5][%cal Gg2g4,
Ya1d1,Ga1e1] we still keep practical chances due to the enormously strong
passed pawns.}) (6... Bd6 $6 {is met comfortably with} 7. Bg5 c6 8. e4 $16 {
with a pleasant edge. ... dxe4 Nxe4 is a favorable inclusion for us, as the d6
bishop is forced to retreat.}) 7. Bf4 O-O 8. e3 {we are heading towards a
better version of the QGD cxd5 ed Bf4 lines (due to the inclusion of ...a6).}
c6 (8... c5 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Rd1 $14 {[%csl Gc3,Rd5,Gf3,Gf4][%cal Gf1e2]}) 9.
h3 {[%csl Gf3,Gf4][%cal Gf1e2] stopping Bg4. After} Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. Bd3
$14 {[%csl Rb6,Rb7,Rc5,Rc8,Gd3,Gf3][%cal Gc3a4] We get our dream setup. White
managed to win comfortably in 1-0 (80) Sargsyan, S (2645)-Kazakouski, V (2539)
Katowice 2022} *

