{[%evp 0,52,25,25,14,15,21,15,15,15,39,-2,3,3,5,5,-1,3,11,4,18,29,28,29,42,37,
37,41,58,14,15,32,63,68,135,83,83,78,76,79,85,22,9,78,68,88,74,74,59,25,33,36,
33,28,28]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+ Nc6 6. e3 O-O 7. Qc2
Re8 8. Bd2 Bf8 9. a3 h6 $5 10. cxd5 exd5 11. h3 Ne7 {[%cal Gc8f5] The point of
deviation from the previous chapter.This move seems to be the strongest from
black's point of view. Black wants to trade the bad bishop with ...Bf5.} 12.
Bd3 g6 {[%cal Gc8f5] and here I recommend going for the ambitious} 13. g4 $5 {
trying to prevent Bf5.} (13. O-O Bf5 $11 {is quite comfortable for black.})
13... Bd7 $1 {[%cal Gc7c5,Ga8c8] This subtle move equalizes completely for
black.} (13... Bg7 {runs into} 14. Ne5 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Gf2f4] looking to
dominate the board.} Bd7 15. b4 $5 {[%cal Gb4c5] preventing c5.} ({the
ambitious} 15. f4 {is possible too. The critical moment seems to be} c5 16.
dxc5 Rc8 17. O-O-O Rxc5 18. Kb1 {where the position is still quite complicated.
}) 15... a5 (15... b6 16. Ne2 $5 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gb4c5,Ga1c1]}) 16. O-O axb4
17. axb4 Rxa1 18. Rxa1 $14 {[%csl Gb4,Rc7,Gd4,Ge5] We keep some pressure due
to the extra space and the knight in the centre.}) (13... c5 $6 14. dxc5 $14 {
[%csl Gc5][%cal Gc3e2,Gb2b4]}) 14. Ne5 $1 c5 {the cleanest way.} ({also
possible was to play} 14... Rc8 {but after} 15. b4 {the game goes on} (15. f4
$5 c5 16. O-O-O {is an interesting alternative attempt.}) 15... a5 $1 (15... b6
16. Ba6 Rb8 17. O-O c5 18. Be1 {[%csl Rc5,Rd5,Ge5][%cal Ga1d1,Gd4c5] gives us
something to play. We want to put pressure on the d5 pawn.}) 16. f4 axb4 17.
axb4 {white seems to have total control but after} Nc6 $1 {black is putting
pressure on b4. However after} 18. Rb1 Nxb4 19. Rxb4 $1 Bxb4 20. Bxg6 Re7 21.
g5 $36 {white has a huge attack on the kingside. Black has to be extremely
accurate to equalize.}) 15. dxc5 Rc8 16. b4 b6 $1 {The point behind the play.
Black sacrifices a pawn to activate all the pieces. The best practical attempt
here seems to be} (16... Nc6 {allows us to play} 17. Nxf7 Kxf7 18. Bxg6+ Kg8
19. O-O-O $44 {[%csl Rd5,Rg8][%cal Gf2f4,Gd2e1,Ge1h4,Yg4g5] where the
compensation is self-evident.}) 17. Ba6 $5 Rb8 18. cxb6 Qxb6 (18... Nc6 $1 {
was quite alright too. Black has a forced draw after} 19. Nxd7 Qxd7 20. bxa7
Qxa7 $1 {with the point that} 21. Nxd5 Nxd5 22. Qxc6 {runs into a perpetual
after} Nxe3 $3 23. Bxe3 Rxe3+ 24. fxe3 Qxe3+ 25. Be2 Re8 $1 26. Ra2 Re6 27. Qa8
Qg3+ 28. Kd2 Qe3+ $11) 19. Be2 {it seems like we have some pressure with Na4
coming up next but after} d4 20. exd4 Nc6 $1 {black is quite alright.} 21. Nxd7
Nxd7 22. Be3 Nxd4 $1 23. Bxd4 Qxd4 24. Rd1 {this really doesn't win a piece as
after} Qf6 $1 25. Rxd7 Qc6 26. Rd5 Rbc8 $11 {black recovers material.} *

